{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048176,"nonce":"1YlBbMd04X8GudCLebfiYLznqac=","title":"Port constraints \u0026 type checking for graph connections","message":"[Imported from GitHub #45] (created 2026-01-27T03:35:57Z)\n\n## Summary\nAdd port constraints/type checking for graph connections to prevent invalid wiring (e.g., multiple outputs to single input, incompatible data types/shapes).\n\n## Motivation\n- Current UI allows nonsensical wiring; this should fail early.\n- Type/shape constraints improve graph correctness and reduce runtime errors.\n\n## Strongest approach (recommended)\n- Extend `ComponentDefinition` with per-port metadata: `dtype` and optional `shape`/`rank` constraints.\n- Validate on connect (`isValidConnection`) and on graph validation (server + client).\n- Use visual affordances (color/shape) to signal port types.\n- Provide clear error messages + hover tooltips.\n\n## Alternatives / optional add-ons\n- **Warnings-only mode**: allow connection but flag mismatches in validation.\n- **Post-compile validation**: evaluate types after graph compilation (less immediate but more accurate).\n- **Auto-adapters**: insert implicit cast/reshape nodes where possible.\n- **Per-component rules**: custom validators for special components rather than strict dtype matching.\n\n## Related opportunities (similar changes elsewhere)\n- Use the same port metadata to drive **simulation inspectors**, **logging**, and **serialization**.\n- Add a **\"port compatibility\"** view in validation tab.\n- Leverage port schemas for automatic **doc generation** of components.\n\n---\n\n## Co-authorship\nCo-Authored-By: Codex (GPT-5) \u003ccodex@openai.com\u003e","files":null}]}